    {
      "id": "part-2",
      "title": "REFI (Core)",
      "description": "The main Real Estate Finance & Investment curriculum.",
      "price": 499,
      "priceId": "price_1OtHJSK...",
      "units": [
        {
          "id": "unit-1",
          "title": "Basic Real Estate Investment Model",
          "description": "How income-producing property is valued and what drives investment returns — from the two components of return to a full levered DCF.",
          "lessons": [
            {
              "id": "lesson-1-1",
              "title": "Theory of Returns",
              "type": "article",
              "duration": "20 min",
              "sections": [
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## What you'll be able to do\n\nBy the end of this unit you will be able to:\n\n- Decompose total return into **income return** (yield) and **appreciation return** (growth).\n- Value a property two ways — **direct capitalization** and **discounted cash flow (DCF)**.\n- Read the relationship **R₀ = r − g** and explain what moves a cap rate.\n- Build a clean **PGI → NOI** proforma and project it forward.\n- Layer in **debt** and judge whether leverage is positive or negative for a deal.\n\n> Estimated time for the unit: ~90 minutes. Prerequisite: *Unit 0.2 — Present Value Math*."
                },
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## Defining “return”\n\n*Return* is the change in price of an investment over time, plus any income it generates. It can be positive (the investment was profitable) or negative (a loss). It is usually expressed as a percentage: profit divided by the amount originally invested.\n\nTwo ideas matter from the start:\n\n1. **Price and return are opposite sides of the same coin.** As the price you pay rises, your return falls — and vice versa. An investor who needs a higher return has to pay a lower price.\n2. **Money is made when you buy, not when you sell.** Once your purchase price is set, so is your expected return. But that expected return is not fully in your control: future cash flows depend on the market, so be prepared for volatility."
                },
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## The two components of return\n\nWhen a property produces rent **and** changes in value, total return over a period combines two pieces:\n\n`Rₜ = CFₜ / Vₜ₋₁  +  (Vₜ − Vₜ₋₁) / Vₜ₋₁`\n\n- **Income return (yield)** — the return from net operating income: `yₜ = CFₜ / Vₜ₋₁`. It comes from contractual leases, so it is relatively stable.\n- **Appreciation return (growth)** — the return from the rise in market value: `gₜ = (Vₜ − Vₜ₋₁) / Vₜ₋₁`. It depends on future market conditions, so it carries most of the risk.\n\n**Total return = income return + appreciation return.**"
                },
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "### Worked example (from class)\n\nA property is bought for **€200,000** at t = 0. The landlord receives **€7,000** rent and sells for **€205,000** at t = 1.\n\n- Income return = 7,000 / 200,000 = **3.5%**\n- Appreciation return = (205,000 − 200,000) / 200,000 = **2.5%**\n- **Total return = 3.5% + 2.5% = 6.0%**\n\nFor multi-period investments (the norm in real estate, which is long-term), we measure return with the **Internal Rate of Return (IRR)** — the single rate that discounts all the investment's future cash flows back to a present value equal to its purchase price."
                },
                {
                  "type": "quiz",
                  "content": "Knowledge Check — Components of Return",
                  "quizData": [
                    {
                      "id": "u1l1-q1",
                      "text": "A property yields 5% in income and appreciates by 3% over the year. What is the total return?",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "2%",
                        "5%",
                        "8%",
                        "15%"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "8%",
                      "explanation": "Total return = income return (5%) + appreciation return (3%) = 8%."
                    },
                    {
                      "id": "u1l1-q2",
                      "text": "Which component of return is generally considered less risky?",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "Income return",
                        "Appreciation return"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "Income return",
                      "explanation": "Income comes from contractual leases; appreciation depends on future market conditions and the exit cap rate, so it carries more risk."
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "id": "lesson-1-2",
              "title": "Valuation: Cap Rate vs. DCF",
              "type": "article",
              "duration": "25 min",
              "sections": [
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## Two roads from income to value\n\nThere are two standard approaches to valuing income property.\n\n### 1 · Income capitalization (cap rate)\n\nUsed when cash flows are treated as an **infinite / perpetual** stream. It cannot be used for a finite horizon.\n\n`Value = NOI₁ / Cap Rate`\n\nwhere NOI₁ is the net operating income one year after purchase. The cap rate captures the **opportunity cost of capital** of a similar investment — it is read off comparable property transactions in the market.\n\n### 2 · Discounted cash flow (DCF)\n\nUsed for a **finite** hold (e.g. 5–10 years). Value is the present value of all future cash flows — rents plus the net sale price — discounted at the investor's required total return *r*.\n\n`Value = Σ CFₜ / (1+r)ⁿ  +  NSP / (1+r)ⁿ`"
                },
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## Splitting the cap rate: R₀ = r − g\n\nTo the extent a property behaves like a **constant-growth annuity**, the cap rate is simply the required return minus the expected growth in cash flows:\n\n`R₀ = r − g`\n\nwhere `r` (= Y₀) is the discount rate / required total return and `g` is the growth rate of NOI.\n\n> This is why a **falling required return raises prices**: if *r* drops, the cap rate R₀ falls, and since Value = NOI₁ / R₀, value goes up. The same happens if growth expectations *g* rise."
                },
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## Building the proforma (PGI → NOI)\n\nEvery model starts from the income waterfall. Work down from gross potential rent to the cash flow available to investors:\n\n- **Potential Gross Income (PGI)** — contract + market rent\n- **− Vacancy & collection loss** (a % of PGI)\n- **= Effective Gross Income (EGI)**\n- **− Operating Expenses** (a % of EGI)\n- **= Net Operating Income (NOI)**\n- **− Capital reserve (CapEx)**\n- **= Property Before-Tax Cash Flow (PBTCF)**\n\nOrder matters: vacancy comes off *gross* rent; operating expenses come off *effective* income. Mixing these up is the most common proforma mistake."
                },
                {
                  "type": "quiz",
                  "content": "Knowledge Check — Valuation",
                  "quizData": [
                    {
                      "id": "u1l2-q1",
                      "text": "Cap rates in a market are 10.5%. A property earns €50,000 of net income per year. What should it sell for?",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "€5,250",
                        "€50,000",
                        "€476,190",
                        "€525,000"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "€476,190",
                      "explanation": "Value = NOI ÷ cap rate = 50,000 ÷ 0.105 = €476,190. Direct capitalization treats stabilized income as a perpetuity."
                    },
                    {
                      "id": "u1l2-q2",
                      "text": "All else equal, the required rate of return on real estate falls. What happens to prices?",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "Prices increase",
                        "Prices decrease",
                        "No change"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "Prices increase",
                      "explanation": "Price = NOI ÷ cap rate, and cap rate = r − g. A lower r lowers the cap rate, which raises value."
                    },
                    {
                      "id": "u1l2-q3",
                      "text": "Which valuation approach is appropriate for a finite 7-year hold?",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "Income capitalization (cap rate)",
                        "Discounted cash flow (DCF)"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "Discounted cash flow (DCF)",
                      "explanation": "Direct capitalization assumes a perpetual stream; a finite hold is valued with DCF — PV of the interim cash flows plus the net sale price."
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "id": "lesson-1-3",
              "title": "Valuation & Leverage Lab",
              "type": "simulator",
              "duration": "30 min",
              "sections": [
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## Interactive lab\n\nThis is the in-browser version of the class Excel model. Drag any assumption and the proforma, both valuations, and the levered return recompute instantly.\n\nTry these experiments:\n\n1. Lower the **going-in cap rate** from 6.5% to 5.5% — watch value jump (you're paying more per € of income).\n2. Set the **exit cap rate** above the going-in rate — see the DCF value fall below the direct-cap value.\n3. Push the **mortgage rate** above the cap rate — the insight flips from *positive* to *negative* leverage."
                },
                {
                  "type": "simulator",
                  "simulatorId": "ValuationLabSimulator"
                },
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "### Reading the leverage result\n\nLeverage is **positive** when the cost of debt is **below** the property's cap rate — each borrowed euro earns more than it costs, lifting equity IRR. It turns **negative** when the mortgage rate rises above the cap rate, and debt starts diluting returns. Lenders also watch the **DSCR** (NOI ÷ debt service); most want at least 1.25×."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "id": "lesson-1-4",
              "title": "Build the Proforma in Excel",
              "type": "article",
              "duration": "20 min",
              "sections": [
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## Hands-on: the class Excel model\n\nNow rebuild the model yourself. The lab below is a lightweight present-value sandbox; the full class workbook (empty-cells and solutions) is in the downloads at the bottom.\n\nKey Excel functions: `=PV(rate, nper, pmt, [fv])`, `=NPV(rate, values)`, `=IRR(values)`, and `=PMT(rate, nper, pv)` for the mortgage. Assume cash flows occur at the **end** of each period unless told otherwise."
                },
