        {
          "id": "unit-2",
          "title": "Real Estate Capital Structures",
          "description": "How deals are financed with layers of debt and equity — the capital stack, leverage, mezzanine and preferred equity, and the GP/LP waterfall that splits the profits.",
          "lessons": [
            {
              "id": "lesson-2-1",
              "title": "The Capital Stack",
              "type": "article",
              "duration": "20 min",
              "sections": [
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## What you'll be able to do\n\n- Rank the layers of the **capital stack** by risk, return and priority of payment.\n- Explain **why** investors use debt (three strategic reasons).\n- Tell apart **mezzanine debt**, **preferred equity** and **common equity**.\n- Read a **GP/LP waterfall** and explain the **promote**.\n\n> Builds on Unit 1 (leverage & levered IRR) and Unit 3 (mortgages)."
                },
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## The capital stack\n\nMost real estate deals are financed with a **mix** of debt and equity, stacked by priority. From safest/lowest return at the bottom to riskiest/highest return at the top:\n\n- **Senior debt** (the mortgage) — paid first, lowest cost, lowest risk.\n- **Mezzanine debt** — subordinate to senior debt, higher rate.\n- **Preferred equity** — hybrid; paid before common equity, fixed-ish return.\n- **Common equity** (LP + GP) — paid **last**, takes the **first loss**, but captures **all the upside**.\n\nTwo rules follow from the order:\n1. **Priority of payment** runs bottom-up: senior debt is served before anyone above it.\n2. **Risk and return rise as you go up** the stack — the last-paid money demands the highest return."
                },
                {
                  "type": "quiz",
                  "content": "Knowledge Check — The Stack",
                  "quizData": [
                    {
                      "id": "u2l1-q1",
                      "text": "In a typical capital stack, which position has the highest risk and the highest expected return?",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "Senior debt",
                        "Mezzanine debt",
                        "Common equity"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "Common equity",
                      "explanation": "Common equity is the 'first loss' position but captures all the upside, so it commands the highest expected return."
                    },
                    {
                      "id": "u2l1-q2",
                      "text": "Which layer is paid first from the property's cash flow?",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "Senior debt",
                        "Preferred equity",
                        "Common equity"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "Senior debt",
                      "explanation": "Senior lenders have priority of payment (and foreclosure rights) ahead of every other stakeholder."
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "id": "lesson-2-2",
              "title": "Why Use Debt? The Leverage Lab",
              "type": "simulator",
              "duration": "30 min",
              "sections": [
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## Three strategic reasons to use debt\n\n1. **Leverage (return on equity).** Unleveraged real estate has limited upside. Borrowing at a cost below the cap rate amplifies the return on your equity — **positive leverage**. (If the cost of debt exceeds the cap rate, leverage turns **negative** and dilutes returns.)\n2. **Diversification.** With €10m of equity you can buy two €5m buildings all-cash, or eight €5m buildings at 75% LTV (€40m total) — spreading idiosyncratic risk across more assets.\n3. **Inflation hedge.** Fixed-rate debt payments stay flat while rents rise with inflation, so real debt burden shrinks over time."
                },
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "### Leverage lab\n\nIncrease the loan-to-value and watch how leverage amplifies **both** the equity IRR **and** the risk."
                },
                {
                  "type": "simulator",
                  "simulatorId": "LeveredReturnsSimulator"
                },
                {
                  "type": "quiz",
                  "content": "Knowledge Check — Leverage",
                  "quizData": [
                    {
                      "id": "u2l2-q1",
                      "text": "Leverage is 'positive' (it lifts equity returns) when:",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "The cost of debt is below the cap rate",
                        "The cost of debt is above the cap rate",
                        "LTV is above 50%"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "The cost of debt is below the cap rate",
                      "explanation": "When borrowing costs less than the property yields (cap rate), each borrowed euro earns more than it costs — positive leverage."
                    },
                    {
                      "id": "u2l2-q2",
                      "text": "With €10m equity, moving from all-cash to 75% LTV lets you buy roughly:",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "The same number of properties",
                        "2x as many properties",
                        "4x as many properties"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "4x as many properties",
                      "explanation": "At 75% LTV your equity covers 25% of each deal, so the same equity controls about four times the asset value — more diversification."
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "id": "lesson-2-3",
              "title": "Mezzanine, Preferred Equity & GP/LP",
              "type": "article",
              "duration": "20 min",
              "sections": [
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## Beyond senior debt\n\n### Mezzanine debt\n- **Position:** subordinate to senior debt, senior to equity.\n- **Security:** often secured by a pledge of the **equity interest** in the borrowing entity, not the property itself — so on default the mezz lender can take over the entity (faster than property foreclosure).\n\n### Preferred equity\n- **Nature:** a hybrid — part of the ownership stack, but behaves like debt (a fixed preferred return).\n- **Priority:** paid before common equity, after all debt.\n- **Control:** usually none, unless a 'kick-out' trigger event occurs.\n\n### The GP/LP structure\n- **Limited Partner (LP):** provides most of the cash (often 90–95%), limited control.\n- **General Partner (GP):** provides expertise, runs the deal, puts in a little capital, and earns a **promote** — a disproportionate share of profits above agreed return hurdles."
                },
                {
                  "type": "quiz",
                  "content": "Knowledge Check — Structures",
                  "quizData": [
                    {
                      "id": "u2l3-q1",
                      "text": "Mezzanine debt is typically secured by:",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "A first mortgage on the property",
                        "A pledge of the equity interest in the borrowing entity",
                        "Nothing — it is unsecured"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "A pledge of the equity interest in the borrowing entity",
                      "explanation": "Mezz is usually secured by the ownership interest in the entity, letting the lender take control of the entity on default rather than foreclosing on the property."
                    },
                    {
                      "id": "u2l3-q2",
                      "text": "The GP's 'promote' is:",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "A share of profits above agreed return hurdles",
                        "A fixed management fee",
                        "The LP's preferred return"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "A share of profits above agreed return hurdles",
                      "explanation": "The promote (carried interest) rewards the GP with an outsized share of the upside once the LP's return hurdles are met."
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "id": "lesson-2-4",
              "title": "The Equity Waterfall",
              "type": "simulator",
              "duration": "30 min",
              "sections": [
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## Splitting the profits: the waterfall\n\nEquity profits are distributed through a **waterfall** — a sequence of tiers:\n\n1. **Return of capital** — LPs get their invested capital back.\n2. **Preferred return** — LPs receive a hurdle return (e.g. 8%) before the GP shares in profit.\n3. **Promote / carried interest** — above the hurdle, the GP takes a larger slice (e.g. 20%) as reward for performance.\n\nUse the simulator to structure the tiers and see how the **promote** shifts the split between LP and GP as returns rise."
                },
                {
                  "type": "simulator",
                  "simulatorId": "WaterfallSimulator"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "id": "lesson-2-5",
              "title": "Case Study: Barcelona",
              "type": "simulator",
              "duration": "45 min",
              "sections": [
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## Real-world capital structuring\n\nApply the unit to a real European deal. Structure the debt and equity, set the waterfall, and see how the capital stack drives investor returns in the Barcelona case."
                },
                {
                  "type": "simulator",
                  "simulatorId": "BarcelonaCaseSimulator"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "id": "lesson-2-6",
              "title": "Summary & Assessment",
              "type": "article",
              "duration": "15 min",
              "sections": [
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## One-page summary\n\n- **Capital stack:** senior debt → mezzanine → preferred equity → common equity. Priority of payment runs bottom-up; risk and return rise top-up.\n- **Why debt:** leverage (when cost of debt < cap rate), diversification, and an inflation hedge.\n- **Mezzanine** is secured by the equity interest; **preferred equity** behaves like debt inside the ownership stack.\n- **GP/LP:** LP funds most of the capital; GP runs the deal and earns a **promote** above return hurdles.\n- **Waterfall:** return of capital → preferred return → promote."
                },
                {
                  "type": "quiz",
                  "content": "Unit 2 Assessment",
                  "quizData": [
                    {
                      "id": "u2a-q1",
                      "text": "Order these from FIRST to LAST paid: common equity, senior debt, mezzanine debt.",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "Senior debt → mezzanine debt → common equity",
                        "Common equity → mezzanine debt → senior debt",
                        "Mezzanine debt → senior debt → common equity"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "Senior debt → mezzanine debt → common equity",
                      "explanation": "Priority of payment: senior debt first, then mezzanine, with common equity paid last (and bearing first loss)."
                    },
                    {
                      "id": "u2a-q2",
                      "text": "A deal's senior loan costs 4.5% and the property's cap rate is 6%. The leverage is:",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "Positive",
                        "Negative",
                        "Neutral"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "Positive",
                      "explanation": "Cost of debt (4.5%) is below the cap rate (6%), so borrowing increases the return on equity — positive leverage."
                    },
                    {
                      "id": "u2a-q3",
                      "text": "In a waterfall, the LP's preferred return is paid:",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "After the GP's promote",
                        "Before the GP shares in profits",
                        "Only if the property is sold at a loss"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "Before the GP shares in profits",
                      "explanation": "The LP receives its preferred (hurdle) return before the GP earns any promote on the upside."
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ],
              "resources": [
                {
                  "title": "III.5 Capital Structure class exercise — Excel (empty + solutions)",
                  "type": "xlsx",
                  "path": "/content/refi/unit-2/III.5-capital-structure.xlsx"
                },
                {
                  "title": "Wildcat Capital Investors — case Excel (solutions)",
                  "type": "xlsx",
                  "path": "/content/refi/unit-2/wildcat-solutions.xlsx"
                },
                {
                  "title": "Case study 1 — Valencia",
                  "type": "pdf",
                  "path": "/content/refi/unit-2/case-valencia.pdf"
                },
                {
                  "title": "Capital Structures slides",
                  "type": "pptx",
                  "path": "/content/refi/unit-2/slides.pptx"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": "unit-3",
          "title": "Commercial Mortgages",
          "description": "How commercial loans are structured, how the four repayment patterns behave, and how loans are valued, prepaid, refinanced and underwritten.",
          "lessons": [
            {
              "id": "lesson-3-1",
              "title": "Note vs. Mortgage & Loan Mechanics",
              "type": "article",
              "duration": "20 min",
              "sections": [
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## What you'll be able to do\n\n- Distinguish the **promissory note** from the **mortgage** (the collateral instrument).\n- Describe the **four repayment patterns** and how each one's payment and balance behave.\n- Compute and interpret the two ratios lenders live by — **LTV** and **DSCR**.\n- Value a seasoned loan in the secondary market and reason about **prepayment** and **refinancing**.\n\n> Prerequisite: Unit 1 (proforma & NOI) and Unit 0.2 (present-value math)."
                },
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## The note and the mortgage are two different things\n\n- **Promissory note** — the contract that sets out the financial obligation: principal, interest rate, term and payment schedule. It is the *debt*.\n- **Mortgage** (or *deed of trust*) — the legal instrument that pledges the property as **collateral** for the note. It is what gives the lender the right to foreclose if the borrower defaults.\n\nYou can sell the note (the cash-flow stream) separately in the secondary market; the mortgage follows it."
                },
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## The two ratios lenders underwrite on\n\n- **Loan-to-Value (LTV)** = Loan ÷ Property value. Caps how much they'll lend (e.g. 60–75%). Lower LTV = more equity cushion = safer.\n- **Debt Service Coverage Ratio (DSCR)** = NOI ÷ Annual debt service. Measures how comfortably the property's income covers the loan payment. Most commercial lenders want **≥ 1.25×**.\n\nA loan must satisfy *both* tests — whichever binds first sets the maximum loan."
                },
                {
                  "type": "quiz",
                  "content": "Knowledge Check — Loan Basics",
                  "quizData": [
                    {
                      "id": "u3l1-q1",
                      "text": "What does a DSCR of 1.25× mean?",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "NOI is 25% higher than the debt service",
                        "NOI equals the debt service",
                        "NOI is 25% below the debt service"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "NOI is 25% higher than the debt service",
                      "explanation": "DSCR = NOI ÷ debt service. 1.25× means the property generates 25% more income than the loan payment — a safety margin lenders require."
                    },
                    {
                      "id": "u3l1-q2",
                      "text": "Which instrument pledges the property as collateral?",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "The promissory note",
                        "The mortgage (deed of trust)"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "The mortgage (deed of trust)",
                      "explanation": "The note is the debt obligation; the mortgage is the security instrument that lets the lender foreclose on the property."
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "id": "lesson-3-2",
              "title": "The Four Repayment Patterns",
              "type": "article",
              "duration": "25 min",
              "sections": [
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## How the loan is paid back\n\nEvery commercial loan follows one of four patterns. They differ in how each payment splits between **interest** and **principal**, and therefore how the **balance** falls.\n\n1. **Interest-Only (IO)** — you pay only interest each period; the full principal is due at maturity (a *balloon*). Lowest payment, no amortization.\n2. **Constant Payment Mortgage (CPM)** — the **same total payment** every period (a level annuity). Early payments are mostly interest; over time more goes to principal. This is the classic amortizing loan.\n3. **Constant Amortization Mortgage (CAM)** — the **same principal repayment** every period, so the payment *falls* over time as interest on the shrinking balance declines.\n4. **Adjustable-Rate Mortgage (ARM)** — the rate resets periodically to an index + margin, so payments move with rates."
                },
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "### Worked example — CPM payment (in euros)\n\nA **€1,000,000** loan, **5%** annual rate, **25-year** term, paid annually. The constant payment solves the annuity formula (Excel: `=PMT(5%, 25, -1,000,000)`):\n\n- **Annual payment ≈ €70,950**\n- Year 1 interest = 5% × €1,000,000 = **€50,000**; principal = 70,950 − 50,000 = **€20,950**\n- Year 2 interest is charged on the *lower* balance (€979,050), so a bit **less** interest and **more** principal — and so on. That shifting mix is amortization.\n\n> The **principal repaid in a period = payment − interest owed**. Memorise that one line; the whole schedule falls out of it."
                },
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "### ARM mechanics\n\nAn ARM's rate = **index + margin** (e.g. 12-month Euribor + 2.5%). To protect borrowers, ARMs carry **caps**: an *annual* cap (how much the rate can move per reset) and a *lifetime* cap (the maximum rate ever). When the rate resets up, the payment rises — the core risk of an ARM."
                },
                {
                  "type": "quiz",
                  "content": "Knowledge Check — Repayment Patterns",
                  "quizData": [
                    {
                      "id": "u3l2-q1",
                      "text": "Which mortgage has the same total payment every period?",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "Interest-Only (IO)",
                        "Constant Payment Mortgage (CPM)",
                        "Constant Amortization Mortgage (CAM)"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "Constant Payment Mortgage (CPM)",
                      "explanation": "CPM is a level annuity — the same payment each period, with the interest/principal split shifting over time."
                    },
                    {
                      "id": "u3l2-q2",
                      "text": "In any amortizing loan, the principal repaid in a period equals:",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "Interest owed − payment",
                        "Payment − interest owed",
                        "Balance ÷ term"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "Payment − interest owed",
                      "explanation": "Whatever part of the payment exceeds the interest due reduces the outstanding balance."
                    },
                    {
                      "id": "u3l2-q3",
                      "text": "An ARM's interest rate is set as:",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "Index + margin",
                        "Cap − floor",
                        "NOI ÷ value"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "Index + margin",
                      "explanation": "The fully-indexed rate is a benchmark index (e.g. Euribor) plus a fixed lender margin, subject to caps."
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "id": "lesson-3-3",
              "title": "Mortgage Lab",
              "type": "simulator",
              "duration": "30 min",
              "sections": [
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## Loan mechanics lab\n\nExplore how the **interest rate**, **amortization period**, **interest-only period** and **loan amount** shape the payment and the amortization schedule. Watch the interest/principal split shift as the balance falls."
                },
                {
                  "type": "simulator",
                  "simulatorId": "MortgageMasterSimulator"
                },
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "Try it: extend the **interest-only period** and watch the balloon at maturity grow; raise the **rate** and see how much more of each early payment is eaten by interest."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "id": "lesson-3-4",
              "title": "Loan Yields, Prepayment & Refinancing",
              "type": "article",
              "duration": "25 min",
              "sections": [
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## Valuing a seasoned loan\n\nWhen a loan is sold in the secondary market, its **price is set by the current market yield**, not its original coupon. Discount the loan's remaining cash flows at today's market rate:\n\n- If **market yield < coupon**, the loan trades at a **premium** (price above the outstanding balance).\n- If **market yield > coupon**, it trades at a **discount**.\n\n## Prepayment risk\n\nBorrowers tend to **prepay when rates fall** (to refinance cheaper). If you bought the loan at a premium, early prepayment means you get par back instead of the premium stream — a loss of yield. **Prepayment penalties / yield maintenance** clauses exist to protect the lender against exactly this."
                },
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## The refinancing decision (an NPV problem)\n\nRefinance when the present value of the interest **savings** exceeds the **transaction costs** (points + fees) over your expected holding period.\n\n1. Compute the current loan payment (status quo).\n2. Compute the new loan payment + closing costs.\n3. Compare the PV of the monthly savings against the upfront cost.\n\n> Short remaining hold → fees often outweigh savings (don't refinance). Long hold → savings usually win. It is always a present-value comparison, never just \"the new rate is lower.\""
                },
                {
                  "type": "quiz",
                  "content": "Knowledge Check — Yields & Refinancing",
                  "quizData": [
                    {
                      "id": "u3l4-q1",
                      "text": "A loan's 8% coupon is above today's 7% market yield. It will trade at:",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "A premium (price > balance)",
                        "A discount (price < balance)",
                        "Exactly par"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "A premium (price > balance)",
                      "explanation": "Its above-market coupon is worth more than par, so buyers pay a premium. Falling market yields push loan prices up."
                    },
                    {
                      "id": "u3l4-q2",
                      "text": "When are borrowers most likely to prepay?",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "When interest rates fall",
                        "When interest rates rise",
                        "When NOI falls"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "When interest rates fall",
                      "explanation": "Falling rates make refinancing attractive, so borrowers prepay — the risk that prepayment penalties protect against."
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "id": "lesson-3-5",
              "title": "Underwriting, Summary & Assessment",
              "type": "article",
              "duration": "15 min",
              "sections": [
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## One-page summary\n\n- **Note = the debt; mortgage = the collateral.**\n- **Four patterns:** IO (balloon), CPM (level payment), CAM (level principal, falling payment), ARM (rate = index + margin, with caps).\n- **Amortization rule:** principal repaid = payment − interest owed.\n- **Underwriting:** a loan must pass both **LTV** and **DSCR (≥ ~1.25×)** — the binding one sets the max loan.\n- **Secondary market:** price = PV of remaining cash flows at today's yield; falling yields → premium.\n- **Prepayment & refinancing** are present-value decisions; penalties protect lenders against rate-driven prepayment."
                },
                {
                  "type": "quiz",
                  "content": "Unit 3 Assessment",
                  "quizData": [
                    {
                      "id": "u3a-q1",
                      "text": "A property has NOI of €125,000 and the proposed annual debt service is €100,000. What is the DSCR?",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "0.80×",
                        "1.25×",
                        "2.50×"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "1.25×",
                      "explanation": "DSCR = NOI ÷ debt service = 125,000 ÷ 100,000 = 1.25× — right at a typical lender minimum."
                    },
                    {
                      "id": "u3a-q2",
                      "text": "In a CAM loan, over time the periodic payment:",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "Stays constant",
                        "Falls",
                        "Rises"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "Falls",
                      "explanation": "CAM repays the same principal each period, so interest on the shrinking balance declines and the total payment falls."
                    },
                    {
                      "id": "u3a-q3",
                      "text": "You should refinance when:",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "The new rate is lower than the old rate",
                        "The PV of interest savings exceeds the transaction costs over your hold",
                        "Rates have moved at all"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "The PV of interest savings exceeds the transaction costs over your hold",
                      "explanation": "Refinancing is an NPV decision: weigh the present value of savings against points and fees over how long you'll hold."
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ],
              "resources": [
                {
                  "title": "II.2 Interest-only mortgage — Excel (empty + solutions)",
                  "type": "xlsx",
                  "path": "/content/refi/unit-3/II.2-interest-only.xlsx"
                },
                {
                  "title": "II.3 Constant payment mortgage — Excel",
                  "type": "xlsx",
                  "path": "/content/refi/unit-3/II.3-constant-payment.xlsx"
                },
                {
                  "title": "II.4 Constant amortization mortgage — Excel",
                  "type": "xlsx",
                  "path": "/content/refi/unit-3/II.4-constant-amortization.xlsx"
                },
                {
                  "title": "II.5 Adjustable-rate mortgage — Excel",
                  "type": "xlsx",
                  "path": "/content/refi/unit-3/II.5-arm.xlsx"
                },
                {
                  "title": "II.8 Mortgage refinancing — Excel",
                  "type": "xlsx",
                  "path": "/content/refi/unit-3/II.8-refinancing.xlsx"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
